Ambulatory Glucose Profile is a dynamic glucose profile generated by processing all glucose readings during CGM monitoring. It can identify individual blood sugar patterns. Generating an AGP profile requires 5 days or more of CGM data.

Reference \10Bergenstal, Richard M., et al. \"Glucose management indicator (GMI): a new term for estimating A1C from continuous glucose monitoring.\" Diabetes care 41.11 (2018): 2275-2280.\10Battelino, Tadej, et al. \"Clinical targets for continuous glucose monitoring data interpretation: recommendations from the international consensus on time in range.\" Diabetes care 42.8 (2019): 1593-1603.\10Bergenstal, Richard M., et al. \"Recommendations for standardizing glucose reporting and analysis to optimize clinical decision making in diabetes: the Ambulatory Glucose Profile (AGP).\" (2013): 198-211.\10Kovatchev, Boris P., et al. \"Algorithmic evaluation of metabolic control and risk of severe hypoglycemia in type 1 and type 2 diabetes using self-monitoring blood glucose data.\" Diabetes technology & therapeutics 5.5 (2003): 817-828.
Estimated glycated hemoglobin, calculated based on CGM glucose readings, used to assess overall blood sugar levels, with a reference value of <7%.

Low Blood Glucose Index is used to assess the risk of severe low blood sugar. \10\10 High risk: LBGI > 5.0 Moderate risk: 2.5 < LBGI ≤ 5.0 \10\10 Low risk: 1.1 < LBGI ≤ 2.5 \10\10Very low risk: LBGI ≤ 1.1
Mean blood glucose, the average of all glucose values during CGM monitoring, used to assess overall blood sugar levels, with a reference value of %1$s-%2$s %3$s.

The target range is typically %1$s-%2$s %3$s or %4$s-%5$s %6$s. High: Time or percentage when glucose is above the target range, reference value <25%%. Normal: Time or percentage when glucose is within the target range, reference value >70%%. Low: Time or percentage when glucose is below the target range, reference value <4%%.
